{center}
{subhead}Dr. Strange, Web Wanderer{def}{p}
Article by Mark Tierno
{left}
{pp}
Well, if you're like me you're getting impatient for OS4 and are in
dire need of a distraction.  Well, welcome to your distraction. Start
browsing a few of these sites and you'll forget all about OS4... well,
at least for a short time.
{pp}
{pp}
{bold}404 Research Lab{nobold}{p}
{italic}http://www.plinko.net/404/{noitalic}{p}
Hunt for a page and sooner or later you'll find one with a 404 error,
but here isapage that collects some of the more amusing 404 error
reports on a weekly basis (like the one that looks like the movie
poster for "Forbidden Planet"), or browse the archives, read the history of
404, see how toovercome it, or just joinin with the living tribute to
404.
{pp}
{pp}
{bold}Superbad- HTML as Art{nobold}{p}
{italic}http://www.superbad.com/{noitalic}{p}
Looks confusing at first but just click anywhere and you'll start
your journey through a maze of pages where you can see HTML code as
art.  Interesting stuff to look at.
{pp}
{pp}
{bold}Your Name In Japanese{nobold}{p}
{italic}http://www.rcs.k12.va.us/csjh/japanesename.htm{noitalic}{p}
Enter your name, press return, and a new java window pops up with your
name as it would be in Japanese (assuming you aren't already).  Quick
trivial fun.
{pp}
{pp}
{bold}Paper Folding{nobold}{p}
{italic}http://www.paperfolding.com/{noitalic}{p}
Origami, the artof paper folding now found on theultimate paperless
entity, the Net.  See pictures of insects, dinosaurs, and more
rendered in actual folded paper, read up on the mathematics behind it,
the history of Origami, and finally a little bit of how-to and
step-by-steps on a few basic figures you can do yourself.
{pp}
{pp}

{center}{bold}Pick Of The Month{nobold}{left}
{pp}
{pp}
{bold}It's Your Turn{nobold}{p}
{italic}http://www.itsyourturn.com/{noitalic}{p}
In times past there used to be play-by-mail, an agonizing way to
protract an ordinary game of chess into many long monthsof awaiting
the next postcard.  Then came online games, but now there's this.
{pp}
Similar theory, only with a web based interface, no Java or flash,
nothing to download.  Just create a user ID and start up a game.  But
what kinds of games are offered?  Try chess, checkers, backgammon,
Battleships, Pente, Go, Reversi, Stack4, and over 60 different games
and variations.
{pp}
We're talking turn-based games, thousands of human opponents, and you
don't have to be logged on at the same time.  You get to choose
when you want to play and who you want to play with. What more could
you ask for in remote board gaming?
{pp}

